    <h3>Understanding Dividend Yield</h3>
    <p>You probably noticed the "Dividend Yield" column. This is arguably the most important metric for income investors. The dividend yield is the annual dividend paid divided by the stock's current price, expressed as a percentage.</p>

    <p>If a stock costs $100 per share and pays $4.00 per year in dividends, its yield is 4.0%. This tells you the return you are getting on your investment strictly from cash flow, ignoring any changes in the stock price itself.</p>

